April 5, 1943

4
00:00:24,408 --> 00:00:28,053
Never can get enough girls 
for all the shifts.

5
00:00:28,053 --> 00:00:33,244
And heaven knows, we have to
work 24 hours a day for victory.

6
00:00:33,244 --> 00:00:34,185
Sure.

7
00:00:35,251 --> 00:00:37,791
They're a real nice bunch. 
You'll see.

8
00:00:37,791 --> 00:00:39,393
Well, this here's Martha.

9
00:00:39,393 --> 00:00:41,185
Martha, meet Alice Miller.

10
00:00:41,185 --> 00:00:43,218
Hi there, joining the line?

11
00:00:43,218 --> 00:00:44,378
I suppose.

12
00:00:44,378 --> 00:00:46,069
Husband overseas?

13
00:00:46,069 --> 00:00:47,810
Watch it, girls.

14
00:00:47,810 --> 00:00:48,619
Goodness.

15
00:00:48,619 --> 00:00:51,921
Better get that girl a pair of slacks.

16
00:00:51,921 --> 00:00:53,642
That's Fannie.

17
00:00:55,613 --> 00:00:57,799
Dottie, this the new girl?

18
00:00:57,799 --> 00:01:00,394
Yes, sir. My neighbor Alice.

19
00:01:00,394 --> 00:01:02,198
Know how to work a vertical lathe.

20
00:01:02,198 --> 00:01:04,173
I've never worked a day in my life.

21
00:01:04,173 --> 00:01:08,427
Oh, it's no tougher than 
a sewing machine, you'll see.

22
00:01:08,981 --> 00:01:10,781
- What is it?
- Air raid siren.

23
00:01:10,781 --> 00:01:12,358
It's just practice.

24
00:01:12,358 --> 00:01:16,320
If it was the real thing, you would
a heard the bombs already.

25
00:02:17,907 --> 00:02:18,901
Lil.

26
00:02:19,167 --> 00:02:20,673
Hey, Dana.

27
00:02:21,129 --> 00:02:22,838
Are these the Rosie the Riveters?

28
00:02:22,838 --> 00:02:26,591
Give them the parts, a few weeks,
they can build you a war plane.

29
00:02:26,591 --> 00:02:28,198
How's your story going?

30
00:02:28,198 --> 00:02:30,134
Well, this was the assignment 
nobody wanted,

31
00:02:30,134 --> 00:02:32,536
but my great aunt was 
one of the workers and

32
00:02:32,536 --> 00:02:36,083
it turns out, there is a bigger story here.

33
00:02:36,083 --> 00:02:39,652
Martha, come meet Lilly Rush.

34
00:02:42,688 --> 00:02:44,741
You're the lady detective.

35
00:02:44,741 --> 00:02:46,103
Nice to meet you.

36
00:02:46,103 --> 00:02:48,596
Martha worked with my aunt Alice.

37
00:02:48,596 --> 00:02:50,511
A real nice gal.

38
00:02:50,511 --> 00:02:54,222
Quiet as a mouse at first,
but couldn't have been sweeter.

39
00:02:54,222 --> 00:02:56,671
Terrible, what happened.

40
00:02:56,916 --> 00:02:59,752
The official story was 
she died in a fall.

41
00:02:59,752 --> 00:03:01,560
But here's the thing.

42
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:05,445
The night they say she fell was 
my last night on the job.

43
00:03:05,445 --> 00:03:09,475
Before I left, 
I asked the owner where Alice was,

44
00:03:09,475 --> 00:03:11,682
wanting to say goodbye.

45
00:03:11,682 --> 00:03:13,258
And?

46
00:03:13,393 --> 00:03:16,536
He told me she quit, 
wasn't working there anymore.

47
00:03:16,536 --> 00:03:20,324
But they found the body the next day
at the factory in her work clothes.

48
00:03:20,324 --> 00:03:24,307
Could your memory be mistaken?

49
00:03:24,564 --> 00:03:27,185
You get old, you start forgetting things,

50
00:03:27,185 --> 00:03:30,471
you don't start making them up.

51
00:03:31,414 --> 00:03:33,109
What was the owner's name?

52
00:03:33,109 --> 00:03:35,745
Henry Walker. 
Mean as a snake.

53
00:03:35,745 --> 00:03:37,051
And a drinker.

54
00:03:37,051 --> 00:03:39,781
I could smell liquor 
on his breath that night.

55
00:03:39,781 --> 00:03:41,627
The guy was hiding something.

56
00:03:41,627 --> 00:03:44,486
Like, maybe Alice didn't fall.

57
00:03:44,486 --> 00:03:47,382
Maybe she was pushed.

